ement of artifacts, skills, and knowledge, Strands of Modernization considers the diffusion of industry and transportation-related technologies as well as business methods in East Asia, in the period between approximately 1850 and 1920. Highlighting currents moving in multiple directions, David B. Sicilia, David G. Wittner, and contributors, expand upon conventional notions of what qualifies as a "technology" or a "business practice," looking more broadly at skills, systems of technology, tacit knowledge, and the ideologies and other belief systems with which they interact. The core ambition driving Strands of Modernization is to illuminate processes of adaption, versus adoption, that occur when technology and business practices cross socio-cultural boundaries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Asian.2bisacsh  aAsian history.  aAsian politics.  aAsian studies.  aEast Asia.  abusiness.  aeconomics.  aindustrialization.  amodernization.  atechnology.1 aChen, Yu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaykin, Jeffer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHon, Tze-Ki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMasato, Kimura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMyungsoo, Kim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSicilia, David B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSicilia, David B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSteele, M. William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWittner, David G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWittner, David G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle